    "claim": "`manualEpochInit()` allows anyone to initialize arbitrary future epochs as long as the immediately previous epoch is initialized, and it copies the previous epoch's pool size verbatim. Later stake changes only refresh `poolSize[token][currentEpoch + 1]` inside `deposit()` and `withdraw()`. As a result, callers can pre-initialize epochs beyond `currentEpoch + 1`, and those farther-future snapshots will not be updated when balances subsequently change, even though `getEpochPoolSize()` will treat them as authoritative because `set == true`.",
    "impact": "Attackers can lock in stale denominators for future reward epochs, causing later reward or accounting calculations to use obsolete pool sizes rather than the actual staked supply. This can overpay or underpay users and lets an attacker bias future epoch accounting without needing privileged access.",
    "paths": [
      "An epoch chain is initialized up to `N + 1` for some token.",
      "Before more deposits or withdrawals occur, an attacker calls `manualEpochInit([token], N + 2)` or farther future epochs, copying the then-current size forward.",
      "Honest users later change stake during epoch `N`, which updates only `poolSize[token][N + 1]` and leaves the pre-initialized `N + 2` snapshot stale.",
      "When epoch `N + 2` is queried, `getEpochPoolSize(token, N + 2)` returns the stale initialized value instead of the real carried-forward pool size."
    ],
